"use strict";(self.webpackChunknowarp_github_io=self.webpackChunknowarp_github_io||[]).push([[8130],{7735:e=>{e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"ton-security-risks","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/ton-security-risks","source":"@site/blog/2025-01-26-ton-security-risks.md","title":"TON Security Risks: A static analysis perspective","description":"Introduction","date":"2025-01-26T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"misti","permalink":"/blog/tags/misti"},{"inline":true,"label":"ton","permalink":"/blog/tags/ton"},{"inline":true,"label":"static analysis","permalink":"/blog/tags/static-analysis"}],"readingTime":6.455,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Georgiy Komarov","url":"https://github.com/jubnzv","socials":{"github":"https://github.com/jubnzv","linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/jubnzv/"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/jubnzv.png","key":"GeorgiyKomarov","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"ton-security-risks","title":"TON Security Risks: A static analysis perspective","authors":"GeorgiyKomarov","tags":["misti","ton","static analysis"],"hide_table_of_contents":false},"unlisted":false},"content":"## Introduction\\nSmart contracts are unforgiving. A single bug can vaporize millions of dollars. If you\'re coming from web development, forget everything you know about \\"move fast and break things\\" - here, breaking things means *actually breaking things*. With money. Real money.\\n\\nThis is where static analysis comes in. It\'s a technique that examines your code before deployment to automatically detect potential vulnerabilities. While no automated tool can guarantee perfect security, static analysis can identify many common security issues early in development, when they\'re cheapest to fix.\\n\\nThis article will:\\n- Introduce fundamental concepts of static analysis for smart contract security\\n- Demonstrate how static analysis tools fit into TON\'s security landscape\\n- Present concrete capabilities and limitations of automated security analysis\\n- Showcase practical applications through Misti\\n- Give practical security advises\\n\\nUnderstanding static program analysis enables you to add an additional layer of automated security verification to your development process, catching some vulnerabilities before they reach production.\\n\\n## Static Program Analysis 101\\nSecurity tooling is an essential part of modern smart contract development, serving as the first line of defense against vulnerabilities. While manual code review remains crucial, automated analysis tools can systematically identify classes of bugs that would be tedious and error-prone to catch by hand.\\n\\nStatic program analysis operates by examining program code without actually executing it. The fundamental approach involves constructing abstract models of program behavior - typically through control flow graphs (CFGs) and data flow analysis. These models allow us to reason about program properties without running into the undecidability issues that would come with trying to analyze all possible runtime behaviors.\\n\\n[TODO: picture: static analysis pipeline]\\n[code -> AST -> CFG -> dataflow analysis]\\n\\nIn essence, the approach is straightforward: we read and analyze the code structure to identify potential security vulnerabilities, without executing the code itself.\\n\\nThe widely used techniques that will be illustrated in this post include:\\n- Control flow analysis: Mapping possible execution paths through the program\\n- Data flow analysis: Tracking how values propagate through variables\\n- Datalog-based analysis: Uses translation to [Datalog](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Datalog) in order to reason about desired security properties\\n- Taint analysis: Following potentially dangerous input data through the program\\n\\n### Limitations of Static Analysis\\nThere are also different techniques of analysis exists, which could be used to [explore concrete paths of execution](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symbolic_execution), [prove some properties on a limited domain of program](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Model_checking#Symbolic_model_checking), [prove some properties of the program with more accuracy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstract_interpretation) and so on, but the core issues are always the same: [static undecidability](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rice%27s_theorem). This fundamental limitation, proven by Rice\'s theorem, establishes that determining any non-trivial semantic property of programs is undecidable. In practical terms, this means that no static analysis tool, regardless of its sophistication, can guarantee the detection of all potential vulnerabilities or prove their absence. We can approximate, we can detect certain classes of issues, but complete verification remains mathematically impossible. This reality shapes how we approach smart contract security, emphasizing the importance of combining multiple analysis techniques with thorough manual review.\\n\\n## Static Analysis for Web3 and TON\\nSmart contracts are just programs executing in blockchain. They have some differences, but fundamentally the same techniques of classic program analysis might be applied to smart contracts analysis.\\n\\nBeing a dynamic field, web3 security is currently actively developing, new approaches are testing, but still, that\'s a wild west: tools impact on actual bug finding is suboptimal [TODO cite yannis]. Despite that, we have a huge set of approaches and commercial/free tools described in papers, we know about past bugs typical for other blockchains, and this could be extrapolated to TON.\\n\\nTON creates it\'s own unique archicecture issues, while most of the generic web3 bugs from the research and practical experience still valid for TON.\\n\\nWhile conventional static analysis techniques (as demonstrated in [1]) have proven valuable in other contexts, TON\'s architectural peculiarities demand more sophisticated approaches. The symbolic value analysis methodology, though groundbreaking, requires substantial adaptation for TON\'s computational model.\\n\\n[cite machine unadible bugs]\\n\\nThe most complicated bugs in TON are related to its unique actor model and asynchronous message-passing [2]. \\n- state mutations due to async messages (partial execution)\\n- man in the middle in message flow\\n- ANYTHING that require manual audit\\n\\nSome of these issues could be mitigated by more advanced techniques, requiring some specification of the communactng contracts. it could be done in other category of tools.\\n\\nAs the recent research[5] showcases, all the exploitable web3 bugs could be clsasified as machine-auditable (MAB) and machine unauditable (MUB). that\'s the recent research dwelling into\\n\\nhere is the grasp: more complicated bugs require understanding of the system. and sometimes the issue is that even developer doesn\'t fully understand it.\\n\\n[TODO picture from the paper w/ bug categories/statistics]\\n\\n[concrete issues?]\\nFor smart contracts specifically, these techniques help identify issues like:\\n- Unprotected state modifications\\n- Arithmetic vulnerabilities\\n- Unauthorized access to critical functions\\n- Resource exhaustion vectors\\n\\n### Misti: TON Static Analysis\\nMisti as a source-level analyzer based on monotone framework that works exactly as described above, as well as combining it with Datalog-based analyses. Certantly it has all the limitations typical for this approach. These are esesntial and done by design.\\n\\nMisti covers different categories of security and optimization issues:\\n- cell storage issues (TODO: examples)\\n- dos\\n- arithmetic issues\\n- access control\\n- code optimization\\n- generic suspicious patterns (things we learn from web3 security issues in past)\\n\\nLet\'s consider some case-studies of concrete analyses it implements.\\n\\n#### 1 Cell bounds\\n\\n#### 2 Divide-before-multiply\\nA classic bug leading to [millions] of loss [link]\\n\\n#### 3 Unprotected call\\n\\n#### 4 Suspicious TON PRG usage\\n\\n#### 5 TON PRG issues\\n\\n### Future Directions\\nThere are many possibilities in TON security automation.\\n\\nOur concrete steps in Misti for the future:\\n- Implementing IFDS with path-sensitivity tracking in order to improve accuracy of interprocdural taint analysis\\n- Implement more Tact detectors using advanced static analysis techniques\\n- Improve integrability and API to support third-party developers\\n- Generic Datalog translation\\n- Better tooling for auditors to actually understand the structure of contracts\\n\\nOverall, Misti still following the development of the Tact language as the most reasonable language in the ecosystem which will become a standard in 2025. Also, there is an ongoing work on a tool capable to analyze both: legacy FunC code and Tact which will use a different approach from Misti. It will be announced later this year.\\n\\n## Conclusion\\nWe\'ve considered the basic information about static program analysis and it\'s application to the TON security landscape. Now, after reading this, here are some concrete steps to increase security you should be thinking about:\\n* **Integrate security tools:** Smart contracts handle real money and are unforgiving - a single bug can be catastrophic. Use every possibility to make your code secure. Static analysis is a powerful first line of defense, catching common vulnerabilities early and automatically. But it\'s just one piece of the security puzzle. Use every security tool you can, understand how it works and what can it actually do.\\n* **Apply development practices:** testing, design, formal specification or at least documentation. This develops a separate post and might be highlighted in this blog later. Prefer a safe language.\\n* **Set up processes:** security not only about analysis\\n* **Do security audit:** While static analysis enhances the security process, it cannot replace thorough manual audits. For production contracts, professional security audits remain essential. You could find our contacts on this site or browse security teams collaborating with TF.\\n\\n## References\\n1. [Symbolic Value Analysis for Smart Contracts](https://yanniss.github.io/symvalic-oopsla21.pdf)\\n2. [Secure Smart Contract Programming in FunC](https://blog.ton.org/secure-smart-contract-programming-in-func)\\n3. Security Contact Integration Guidelines\\n4. [TON Smart Contract Security Best Practices](https://github.com/slowmist/Toncoin-Smart-Contract-Security-Best-Practices/blob/main/README.md)\\n5. Zhang et al - Demystifying Exploitable Bugs in Smart Contracts ([pdf](https://github.com/ZhangZhuoSJTU/Web3Bugs/blob/main/papers/icse23.pdf))\\n6. spa.pdf book\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e"}]}}')}}]);